==English==

===Etymology===
From Ancient Greek idiom (see sense 1)

===Verb===
'''[[turn]] [[up]] one's [[nose]] (at something)'''
# {{idiom}} To [[sneer]]
#*'''1958:''' annotated translation based on documents deriving from postulated '''c.85''' Greek text: Lockman Foundation, ''The Amplified New Testament'' used in '''1965''' Zondervan Corporation, ''The Amplified Bible, Luke 23:35'' - the rulers scoffed and sneered (literal translation: turned up their noses) at Him, saying, He rescued others; let Him now rescue Himself, if He is the Christ (the Messiah) of God, His Chosen One!
# {{idiom}} To [[refuse]], especially as due to [[pride]] or [[status]]
#:''I tried to help, but they '''turned up their noses''' at my advice.''

===Related terms===
*[[turn]] 
*[[turn up]]

